widgets.name: Text 10
widgets.textContent: This sheet provides an overview of the various HTTP status codes returned by the Datameer server to the users' web browser. HTTP status codes can be grouped by their initial number. 2xx status codes indicate that the server processed the request successfully. 3xx status codes indicate that the server is waiting on further action by the client (e.g. web browser). 4xx codes are used to indicate that the client has caused an error, e.g., trying to navigate to an unshared workbook. 5xx codes are returned when there is an error with the server.

widgets.name: Text 10
widgets.textContent: The general term housekeeping defines a scheduled service of Datameer (e.g. every hour) that deletes unnecessary data objects. All data objects that will be deleted have to get a mark of deletion first. When a data object is getting deleted, is based on your individual retention policy. This is either defined by count (e.g., keep 10 data objects, if number 11 comes in, delete the first one), by time (e.g. after every business day) or both. The other interesting charts display the time that it takes to prepare a Datameer job before it is sent to the cluster. Higher could indicate possible problems with general system performance.

widgets.name: Text 10
widgets.textContent: Java uses an automatic garbage collector to manage memory in the object lifecycle. The programmer determines when objects are created, and the Java runtime is responsible for recovering the memory once objects are no longer in use. Once no references to an object remain, the unreachable memory becomes eligible to be freed automatically by the garbage collector. An increasing amount of garbage collection decreases general system response time.
